WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.470 --> 00:00:01.790
BILL BILLENSTEIN: Well,
welcome, everybody.

00:00:01.790 --> 00:00:03.240
I see a lot of familiar faces.

00:00:03.240 --> 00:00:05.425
But for those of you who don't
know, I am Chef Bill

00:00:05.425 --> 00:00:08.770
Billenstein from the Silicon
Beach Cafe here at Google.

00:00:08.770 --> 00:00:10.305
And today we're very proud
to have Amelia

00:00:10.305 --> 00:00:12.960
Saltsman, local cook.

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:15.140
She made sure that I tell you
that she is not a chef.

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:15.580
She's a cook.

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:18.300
And she wants you to be
able to cook, too.

00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:20.970
Amelia has written this
wonderful farmers' market

00:00:20.970 --> 00:00:23.900
cookbook, "The Santa Monica
Farmers' Market Cookbook."

00:00:23.900 --> 00:00:28.260
She's also a contributor to
KCRW's "Good Food." She is on

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:31.360
the board of the Garden
City Food Foundation.

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:32.350
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Garden
School Foundation.

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:34.450
BILL BILLENSTEIN: Garden
School Food Foundation.

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:37.540
She's here today to go through
a couple rapid fire recipes

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:40.490
and show you the bounty of the
seasons and some delicious

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:41.730
things that you can
do with your local

00:00:41.730 --> 00:00:43.130
farmer's market produce.

00:00:43.130 --> 00:00:45.350
So without further
ado, Amelia.

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:46.510
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Thank
you, Chef.

00:00:46.510 --> 00:00:50.030
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:53.680
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Well, I am
delighted to be here.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:01:00.400
And Chef, you pretty well nailed
it, what I'm all about.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:06.190
What I do is I really like
to help people see the

00:01:06.190 --> 00:01:08.560
connections between
their food.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:09.940
Well, I should say
among because

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:11.640
there are lots of things.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:15.760
The food that they eat, what it
does for our health, what

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:17.130
it does for the planet.

00:01:17.130 --> 00:01:19.950
All the things we sort of
worry about in life, the

00:01:19.950 --> 00:01:22.110
answer is actually
really simple--

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:25.420
start with flavorful,
fresh ingredients.

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:31.320
It's the fastest, easiest
way to healthy,

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:34.690
delicious cooking fast.

00:01:34.690 --> 00:01:36.140
So I'm going to get
this started.

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:40.850
I'm going to put a little olive
oil in here and throw

00:01:40.850 --> 00:01:43.310
some onions in that I've
already chopped.

00:01:43.310 --> 00:01:46.450
And I'm going to get that going
while I introduce a

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:48.850
little bit more of
what we're doing.

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:50.980
And it's going to take
us a little time to

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:52.230
get adjusted here.

00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:59.850
So how many of you shop at
farmers' markets beyond what

00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:01.070
is brought to you here?

00:02:01.070 --> 00:02:02.800
You are so lucky.

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:03.750
Yeah?

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:04.640
OK, great.

00:02:04.640 --> 00:02:07.470
So I'm preaching to the
converted, right?

00:02:07.470 --> 00:02:12.010
But how many of you are a little
bit confused about what

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:14.240
to do with some of the stuff?

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:15.240
Don't have time?

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:17.140
Maybe it's hard?

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:19.580
You feel like the window of what
you're trying is a little

00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:22.460
bit narrow, like there's
a lot of--

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:22.700
yeah?

00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:24.480
A lot of ingredients,
but you're not sure

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:25.990
what to do with them?

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:30.080
So what I want to do today is
try to get through as many

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:38.040
things as we can, answering
questions as we go and try to

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:40.400
show you some of the techniques,
the simple

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:45.020
techniques that you need that
you can just then vary

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:49.310
everything through all
of these vegetables.

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:53.920
Now, I'm not a vegetarian and
this isn't vegetarian cooking.

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:56.660
And my cookbook, "The Santa
Monica Farmers' Market

00:02:56.660 --> 00:03:00.560
Cookbook" is--

00:03:00.560 --> 00:03:02.330
it covers everything.

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:07.910
It covers sustainably raised
meats and eggs and poultry,

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:12.570
all the things that we should
be looking to find as

00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:16.190
carefully grown as we can.

00:03:16.190 --> 00:03:19.165
Because the key to all
of this is flavor.

00:03:22.670 --> 00:03:25.560
Chef and I were just talking,
if you start with the most

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:30.870
delicious ingredients, you'd
really have to do very little.

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:36.950
So that's the trick to cooking
fast and simply.

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:40.810
Another little trick is
to layer flavors.

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:42.720
So I've got some onions
sauteing.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:46.660
So this first dish we're going
to do is a saute dish.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.700
That's a great technique.

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:53.780
So what you want to do is, with
whatever your cooking,

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:58.270
don't add all the salt,
let's say, at once.

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:00.150
Add a little bit at a time.

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:07.610
That's such an easy technique,
but it will deepen and make

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:11.000
more complex all the flavors
that you're doing.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.930
So we're going to do a Swiss
chard dish first.

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:18.839
Are you all familiar
with Swiss chard?

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:19.399
You all use it?

00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:20.604
OK.

00:04:20.604 --> 00:04:24.350
Because Cat told me, she's like,
always like I'm not sure

00:04:24.350 --> 00:04:26.500
what to do with Swiss chard.

00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:29.640
And this technique
works with kale.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:31.780
It works with other
quick cooking

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:35.050
greens, as for all fabulous.

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:37.370
So basically, we want to
look for contrast.

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:39.060
We're going to do onions.

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:40.690
We're going to do
earthy greens.

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:43.750
We're going to give it some
heat from red pepper.

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:47.090
And we're going to give it some
sweetness from raisins.

00:04:47.090 --> 00:04:48.080
So that's another great

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:51.580
technique, contrasting flavors.

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:53.990
Very exciting, really
easy to do.

00:04:53.990 --> 00:04:56.750
That's why we all like
salty sweet, right?

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:59.030
Because it's contrasting
flavor.

00:04:59.030 --> 00:05:04.520
So one of the things about
cooking fast is,

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:05.880
how do you do it?

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:10.040
So like that.

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:12.190
Don't take a knife and
start cutting.

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:13.635
Want to see it again?

00:05:13.635 --> 00:05:14.310
I love this trick.

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.875
A farmer taught me.

00:05:16.875 --> 00:05:17.960
OK?

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:24.840
Now, with Swiss chard, you
can use the stalk.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:27.560
It sort of has the texture
of celery.

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:30.430
So I've cut up a bunch
here, because we

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:31.660
already separated out.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:37.520
So I'm going to start it with
the onions because it takes a

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:41.600
little bit longer to cook
than the leaves.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.100
And another trick is that we
don't want to add a whole lot

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:53.350
of liquid to the pan, because
we want the flavors to come

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:54.130
from the vegetables.

00:05:54.130 --> 00:05:56.920
Because if you add a lot of
liquid, you're going to have

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:58.170
boiled vegetables.

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:01.090
And there's nothing really
exciting about that.

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:04.650
So now that I've got these
fabulous-looking leaves, all I

00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:06.880
need to do-- can you all see?

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:08.570
OK.

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:09.940
Let me set this aside.

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:11.780
AUDIENCE: Can you
move that bowl?

00:06:11.780 --> 00:06:12.160
AMELIA SALTSMAN: This one?

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:14.810
OK, I'm going to set it aside
right here until we're

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:16.430
ready to use it.

00:06:16.430 --> 00:06:19.700
OK, so now, like if
I were rolling a

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:20.950
lot of tobacco leaves.

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:26.700
Now I'm going to cut
it assembly line

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:28.340
into these nice strips.

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:33.040
And now that's ready.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:36.320
And that's only going to take
a couple of minutes to cook.

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:41.880
So what you want to do is soften
the onions, get them

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:43.130
starting to turn sweet.

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:52.720
And the chard stems.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:54.790
So now what you also
have is texture.

00:06:54.790 --> 00:06:57.380
You've got a contrasting
texture.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:01.430
So in about two minutes, we've
hit all these great marks.

00:07:01.430 --> 00:07:03.930
Right But all we've done
is cook a little

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:07.160
onion and chard stems.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.470
OK.

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:14.180
So we are going to
add the chard.

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:19.710
And it might take a little
bit more time to--

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:20.960
we might have to do
it in batches.

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:28.480
Little salt.

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:34.060
And it's going to wilt
down pretty quickly.

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:38.610
And you notice, we still haven't
added any water, any

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:39.860
liquid to the pan.

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:48.410
And as it's cooking down, I'm
just going to add more.

00:07:48.410 --> 00:07:51.870
So this is two bunches
of chard.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:55.680
And you know, this happens
to have white stems.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:08:02.216
But you've seen chard
also comes rainbow.

00:08:02.216 --> 00:08:06.574
Does this remind you an
anything, any other vegetable?

00:08:06.574 --> 00:08:07.440
AUDIENCE: Beets.

00:08:07.440 --> 00:08:08.205
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Beets.

00:08:08.205 --> 00:08:10.780
Beets, I didn't hear you?

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:11.610
OK.

00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:13.640
So very close relative.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:15.850
Farmers would say that
chard is really a

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:17.120
beet without a root.

00:08:17.120 --> 00:08:18.810
That's how closely related.

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:21.860
So that means if you
buy beets, don't

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:24.050
throw the tops away.

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:26.920
You can cook them
just like this.

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:28.640
I like to call that a twofer.

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:32.650
And actually, with fresh beets,
the tops are the most

00:08:32.650 --> 00:08:33.350
nutritious.

00:08:33.350 --> 00:08:35.524
It's like any dark,
leafy green.

00:08:35.524 --> 00:08:36.750
It's really good for you.

00:08:36.750 --> 00:08:38.000
Very good value.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:43.070
And here we go.

00:08:45.470 --> 00:08:46.340
Can I give that to you?

00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:48.290
Thanks.

00:08:48.290 --> 00:08:50.342
This is Janine, everybody.

00:08:50.342 --> 00:08:52.970
Oh, and guess what I
forgot to put in?

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:57.055
I forgot to add the garlic.

00:08:57.055 --> 00:09:00.850
So I'm just going to stick it
right here on the side.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:02.540
And I want you to take
a look at this.

00:09:02.540 --> 00:09:04.810
Now, does this look like
sliced garlic that

00:09:04.810 --> 00:09:06.740
you're used to seeing?

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:06.880
No.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:08.660
So I'm going to stick it in.

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:12.296
I'm going to show you a little
interesting factoid.

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:22.835
And you notice I'm not
using a lot of oil.

00:09:28.614 --> 00:09:30.595
Do you see how the color
is brightening?

00:09:34.810 --> 00:09:38.480
Once the color is bright, we're

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:44.516
going to add our raisins.

00:09:44.516 --> 00:09:49.170
And let's add a nice pinch
of red pepper.

00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:01.430
Now, I'm going to
cover the pan--

00:10:01.430 --> 00:10:02.980
very big technique.

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:06.300
But that's an important
technique.

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:09.730
And can you see how
it's cooking down?

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:14.940
I'm going to cover the
pan, which will allow

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:16.980
the steam to develop.

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:22.990
And I'm hoping that that's going
to be enough moisture to

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:24.870
soften the chard enough.

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:28.010
And it just needs to cook,
maybe 5 minutes

00:10:28.010 --> 00:10:29.870
or so, 5 or 10 minutes.

00:10:29.870 --> 00:10:31.450
If it cooks longer that's OK.

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:34.700
But if you're in a hurry,
that's OK too.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:38.800
And I'm going to check
it in a few minutes.

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:42.140
If it seems like it's dry or
sticking, I'll add a little

00:10:42.140 --> 00:10:43.050
bit of water.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:44.905
Otherwise, I'm good.

00:10:44.905 --> 00:10:47.550
So let me show you the garlic.

00:10:47.550 --> 00:10:47.940
AUDIENCE: Question.

00:10:47.940 --> 00:10:48.916
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Yeah.

00:10:48.916 --> 00:10:53.310
AUDIENCE: Do you chop the raisin
or just use them whole?

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:55.170
AMELIA SALTSMAN: OK, I just
threw the raisins in.

00:10:55.170 --> 00:10:57.430
And by the way, these
are raisins

00:10:57.430 --> 00:11:00.010
produced by a grape grower.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:02.630
I bought the raisins at the
farmers' market directly from

00:11:02.630 --> 00:11:03.880
the producer.

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:08.080
So they are this season's
grapes, or from last summer.

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:11.030
And it makes a really
big difference.

00:11:11.030 --> 00:11:15.500
So the steam is going to soften
the raisins as well.

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:17.270
So it's doing its thing.

00:11:17.270 --> 00:11:19.640
I'm not doing much.

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:21.500
So garlic.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:23.430
Everything has a season.

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:26.760
And we're used to seeing
dried bulbs of garlic.

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:32.030
But what we've got here
is late spring garlic.

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:33.520
In the beginning
of the season--

00:11:37.291 --> 00:11:40.900
OK, these are baby leeks.

00:11:40.900 --> 00:11:41.720
They're not garlic.

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:45.310
But in the beginning, garlic
looks like this.

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:48.276
Slim hips and no cloves.

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:56.880
As the plant grows, the bulb
forms, the cloves form.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:11:58.130
Can I give you that?

00:12:01.060 --> 00:12:04.670
And you can start to see
the cloves forming.

00:12:04.670 --> 00:12:06.770
So I used late spring garlic.

00:12:06.770 --> 00:12:08.580
When it's young, you
can use the tops.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:10.440
These are already getting
too tough to use.

00:12:14.904 --> 00:12:18.340
So I'm going to take
the carrots.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:20.170
So we're going to let that cook
and we're going to make a

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:21.090
carrot dish.

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:24.230
Do you have any other questions
about that?

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:26.980
Besides chopping raisins?

00:12:26.980 --> 00:12:29.680
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:31.890
AMELIA SALTSMAN: No.

00:12:31.890 --> 00:12:34.100
So it's very juicy.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:37.270
Green garlic is very
mild in flavor.

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:41.530
It has kind of an herbaceous,
sweet garlic flavor.

00:12:41.530 --> 00:12:43.940
And this is a perfect
time to use it.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:48.650
As the plant develops, it
gets stronger in flavor.

00:12:48.650 --> 00:12:54.210
So grilling, another
great technique.

00:12:54.210 --> 00:12:56.720
Roasting, another great
technique, but we don't have

00:12:56.720 --> 00:12:57.250
an oven here.

00:12:57.250 --> 00:12:59.660
But we'll talk about
that in a second.

00:12:59.660 --> 00:13:06.140
So instead of putting oil on the
grill, I'm putting oil--

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:08.330
a little bit of oil--

00:13:08.330 --> 00:13:11.380
on the carrots.

00:13:11.380 --> 00:13:13.900
And I'll tell you more about
the carrots in a minute.

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:15.910
So I like sweet and spicy.

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:19.040
So carrots are really
sweet by themselves.

00:13:19.040 --> 00:13:23.240
A little salt right
in the bowl.

00:13:23.240 --> 00:13:26.500
Now, I've blanched these carrots
before I started.

00:13:29.150 --> 00:13:30.785
You all familiar
with that term?

00:13:30.785 --> 00:13:36.670
Blanching means to boil just
briefly in salted water, and

00:13:36.670 --> 00:13:37.930
then drain it.

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:41.800
And then, shock it with ice and
cold water so that you get

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:44.120
this fabulous--

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:46.276
you preserve the color.

00:13:46.276 --> 00:13:50.660
Oh, nice sound.

00:13:50.660 --> 00:13:51.030
Yes?

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:53.690
AUDIENCE: Did you blanch them
after you cut them?

00:13:53.690 --> 00:13:54.510
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Yes.

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:56.420
So the question was,
do you blanch them

00:13:56.420 --> 00:13:58.280
after you cut them?

00:13:58.280 --> 00:13:59.510
And yes, I'm going
to show you--

00:13:59.510 --> 00:14:00.770
I'm going to go through
the steps.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:03.560
What I want to do is get
them on the grill.

00:14:06.370 --> 00:14:09.430
And I think you already noticed
that what I've done is

00:14:09.430 --> 00:14:15.125
cut them so that I have a really
big cooking surface.

00:14:21.707 --> 00:14:24.600
Now, that's a carrot, right?

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:25.170
OK.

00:14:25.170 --> 00:14:27.950
So we'll let those go for
a couple minutes.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:29.200
I'll just set this-- this
is fine right here.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.140
Fabulous variety of carrots.

00:14:35.140 --> 00:14:38.060
This is called a Chantenay
variety.

00:14:38.060 --> 00:14:40.260
Lots of great carrots
out there.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:42.890
But your carrot needs to
taste-- this is my

00:14:42.890 --> 00:14:44.390
compost bowl here.

00:14:44.390 --> 00:14:47.230
Tell me if it's in your way.

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:49.360
Your carrots should taste
really great.

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:53.980
When you cook it briefly,
certain vegetables do better

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:56.270
and their flavors are enhanced,
particularly

00:14:56.270 --> 00:15:03.100
vegetables with fat soluble
vitamins like carrots.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:05.630
So carrots are kind of dense.

00:15:05.630 --> 00:15:09.180
They're not filled with water.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:11.110
But you want it to be really
sweet and you want to heighten

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:12.350
the flavor.

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:15.460
So I'm cutting it at an angle.

00:15:15.460 --> 00:15:16.870
And can you hear?

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:19.050
This is not like a super
hard carrot.

00:15:19.050 --> 00:15:21.870
Did you see how quickly and
nicely my knife was moving

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:23.780
through it?

00:15:23.780 --> 00:15:25.310
So you want this
nice big slabs.

00:15:25.310 --> 00:15:28.390
And anything-- little tiny
piece, just eat it because

00:15:28.390 --> 00:15:30.030
it's really good, and
good for you.

00:15:30.030 --> 00:15:37.530
So I'm going to check
our chard.

00:15:42.223 --> 00:15:45.150
Isn't that looking beautiful?

00:15:45.150 --> 00:15:46.460
Does it smell good?

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:47.670
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:50.512
AMELIA SALTSMAN: And look at
how pretty the green garlic

00:15:50.512 --> 00:15:51.625
got in the dish.

00:15:51.625 --> 00:15:54.190
Did you see how all its
pretty little strands?

00:15:54.190 --> 00:15:55.525
So we eat with our eyes, too.

00:15:55.525 --> 00:15:58.170
We're using all our senses
already and we've only made

00:15:58.170 --> 00:15:59.060
one and a half dishes.

00:15:59.060 --> 00:16:01.340
So this will be ready
in a minute or two.

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:07.930
And let's see.

00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:09.130
What are we ready for?

00:16:09.130 --> 00:16:10.390
Let's see how these are doing.

00:16:13.940 --> 00:16:22.800
So when you've grilled, one of
the problems with grilling--

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:25.150
everything gets burnt before
it gets cooked.

00:16:25.150 --> 00:16:27.160
Oh, somebody's nodding
in agreement.

00:16:27.160 --> 00:16:28.310
Indeed.

00:16:28.310 --> 00:16:31.290
A couple of little tricks.

00:16:31.290 --> 00:16:33.500
Don't have the heat too high.

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:36.110
And vegetables, like
carrots that are

00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:40.810
dense, blanch them first.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:44.340
And then, that way-- and so I
just boiled them until you saw

00:16:44.340 --> 00:16:46.900
they were kind of pliable.

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:48.450
Just slightly pliable.

00:16:48.450 --> 00:16:53.510
So this big pot full of this
was maybe three minutes.

00:16:53.510 --> 00:16:56.150
The nice thing is you
can do that ahead.

00:16:56.150 --> 00:16:58.250
Do it the day ahead.

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:01.470
And let's say you're having
people over, then you just

00:17:01.470 --> 00:17:03.815
toss those with olive
oil and do it.

00:17:03.815 --> 00:17:05.010
And you know how the
other thing is?

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:09.980
Grilling vegetables takes a lot
longer than grilling meat.

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:12.015
Blanch them and it will
take a few minutes.

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:19.130
After that, you can just go on
to grill whatever else you

00:17:19.130 --> 00:17:22.491
want to throw on the barbie.

00:17:22.491 --> 00:17:24.926
AUDIENCE: Could you do
that for corn too?

00:17:24.926 --> 00:17:25.413
AMELIA SALTSMAN: Pardon?

00:17:25.413 --> 00:17:26.880
AUDIENCE: Would you do
that for corn too?

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:27.684
AMELIA SALTSMAN: You know what?

00:17:27.684 --> 00:17:27.908
I would.

00:17:27.908 --> 00:17:32.180
I actually think that
corn needs moisture.

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:38.310
So you can do that by doing it
in the husk because the husk

00:17:38.310 --> 00:17:41.080
acts as a natural sealer.

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:45.830
So that's one way
to grill corn.

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:53.010
Another way is to just boil it,
parboil it or blanch it.

00:17:53.010 --> 00:17:55.720
And then, just finish it off on
the grill to get that sort

00:17:55.720 --> 00:17:58.800
of smoky complexity that
you're looking to

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:02.280
counterbalance with the
sweetness of the vegetable.

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:04.930
So we've got the same thing
happening with the carrots.

00:18:04.930 --> 00:18:09.240
Sweet carrots, smoke, heat,
all of those things.

00:18:09.240 --> 00:18:11.725
So let's see, I'm going to
need-- how we doing with this?

00:18:11.725 --> 00:18:13.980
JANINE: I think they're
almost ready.

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:15.230
AMELIA SALTSMAN: OK.

00:18:18.230 --> 00:18:22.440
So what we want-- and
this is not the most

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:25.590
ideal cooking situation.

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:27.440
Now, I don't know if any
of you can see it.

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:29.425
Let's turn that down
a little bit.

00:18:29.425 --> 00:18:35.850
But do you see that the carrots
are blistering a

00:18:35.850 --> 00:18:36.760
little as well?

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:39.440
That's also because they
were boiled first.

00:18:39.440 --> 00:18:42.650
And that sort of blistering,
it's almost like when you're

00:18:42.650 --> 00:18:46.770
making pastry and you get these
little layers of air.

00:18:46.770 --> 00:18:50.020
It also just enriches
the flavor.

00:18:50.020 --> 00:18:52.190
Grilling potatoes--

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:56.830
I would definitely blanch them
first if I wanted to make

00:18:56.830 --> 00:18:58.115
spectacular potatoes.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:04.505
And you see there, what happens
when you're grilling

00:19:04.505 --> 00:19:08.490
or roasting is that you're
losing the moisture in the

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:11.800
vegetable and concentrating
the flavor.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:17.440
So if you don't have great
produce, this will improve

00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:18.700
what you have.

00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:23.010
If you have this kind of
produce, it will really sing.

00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:24.850
It will really sing.

00:19:24.850 --> 00:19:27.900
These dishes will be great,
whatever you use.

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:29.530
But if you use this kind of

00:19:29.530 --> 00:19:36.410
ingredient, it will be fabulous.

00:19:36.410 --> 00:19:39.160
And I hope you'll agree.

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:40.910
One of the things that I did--

00:19:40.910 --> 00:19:43.800
speaking of roasting.

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:46.960
I roasted off some
summer squash.

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:49.310
We're just starting
to see this.

00:19:49.310 --> 00:19:53.030
And I wanted you to see
what that looks like.

00:19:53.030 --> 00:19:57.510
I think you can see
it from here.

00:19:57.510 --> 00:20:02.300
All I did was toss it with a
tiny bit of olive oil, a

00:20:02.300 --> 00:20:06.940
little salt, and I put it cut
side down on a sheet pan.

00:20:06.940 --> 00:20:12.140
And I roasted it for 15,
18 minutes at 425.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:16.590
And because there's so much
natural sugar in the squash, I

00:20:16.590 --> 00:20:19.080
got that beautiful
caramelization.

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:23.340
You won't have that with
industrially produced,

00:20:23.340 --> 00:20:26.845
industrially shipped and
distributed ingredients.

00:20:26.845 --> 00:20:28.110
You just can't.

00:20:28.110 --> 00:20:29.920
So that's what you're
looking for.

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:37.160
So all I did was one knife
cut and I was good.

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:38.850
So with carrots, you
don't need to

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:41.380
blanch them before roasting.

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:46.520
You don't need to blanch
zucchini or summer squash.

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:50.580
But what you do get is--

00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:52.380
in fact, roasting is one
of my favorite things.

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:53.350
I have a lot more control.

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:56.110
I don't have to worry
about all of this.

00:20:56.110 --> 00:20:57.075
It's just a lot easier.

00:20:57.075 --> 00:20:59.580
You can serve it at
room temperature.

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:02.020
And what I want to show you is
we're going to make a couple

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:04.840
of different flavor profiles.

00:21:04.840 --> 00:21:06.450
We're going to finish
one batch one way

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:08.525
and one batch another.

00:21:08.525 --> 00:21:12.310
But I am going to move
on to tomatoes.

00:21:16.156 --> 00:21:18.650
Get that.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:21.320
So it's not really--

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:23.190
well, let's finish
with this first.

00:21:23.190 --> 00:21:24.440
This is done.

00:21:31.700 --> 00:21:33.890
All right, what do you think?

00:21:33.890 --> 00:21:35.140
Nice?

00:21:36.730 --> 00:21:39.920
Now, you can turn this
into a main dish.

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:44.500
I love this dish because it
works a lot of different ways.

00:21:44.500 --> 00:21:47.000
You can serve this
as a side dish.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.510
You can toss this with pasta.

00:21:50.510 --> 00:21:55.500
You can chop it up and add some
more seasonings and serve

00:21:55.500 --> 00:21:57.890
it like as a bruschetta
topping.

00:22:00.610 --> 00:22:03.015
And basically, what you're doing
is eating your greens.

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:08.420
Now, what I did today--

00:22:08.420 --> 00:22:10.770
are you are familiar
with farro?

00:22:10.770 --> 00:22:11.840
Ancient wheat.

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:14.690
Anybody gluten free here?

00:22:14.690 --> 00:22:18.220
OK, so this really is--
it's a vegan dish.

00:22:18.220 --> 00:22:20.430
I wasn't attempting to
make a vegan dish.

00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:21.540
What I'm attempting
to do is have

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:23.530
something really delicious.

00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:26.955
And as added value, it happens
to hit all these other marks.

00:22:32.020 --> 00:22:34.140
Quinoa would be great.

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:35.740
Rice would be great.

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:37.940
So let's say this is
a building block.

00:22:37.940 --> 00:22:39.640
We've got farro.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:40.890
We've got our greens.

00:22:43.630 --> 00:22:45.880
And I think it would look really
beautiful if we just

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:48.810
did that, don't you?

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:51.760
Now, if I wanted to really make
this into a nice main

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:57.420
dish, I could add chick peas.

00:22:57.420 --> 00:23:01.260
I could add some of those
carrots, toss it all together

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:02.830
and have a big bowl
of something.

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:04.825
I could season it with cheese.

00:23:07.580 --> 00:23:10.868
What other items do you--
what do you like?

00:23:10.868 --> 00:23:11.354
AUDIENCE: Steak on top.

